🧠 Final Recommended Architecture (clean + implementable)
🔥 Core idea

LLM generates structure → Layout engine generates positions → Flutter owns everything after that

🧩 Full Pipeline (step-by-step)
1. 🧠 Prompt → LLM (strict JSON schema)

You define something like:

{
  "nodes": [
    { "id": "user", "type": "actor", "label": "User" },
    { "id": "service", "type": "component", "label": "UserService" }
  ],
  "edges": [
    { "from": "user", "to": "service", "label": "requests" }
  ]
}

🔑 Rules:
No coordinates
No layout
Only relationships
2. 🧹 Normalize / Validate

Before layout:

ensure all ids exist
remove duplicates
optionally:
assign default sizes (width/height)
3. 🔥 Layout (critical step)

Use:

Dagre (simplest + enough)
How it works:

Input:

nodes + edges


Output:

nodes + x, y positions

💡 Implementation options
✅ BEST (simple + powerful)

Run Dagre in a small Node.js service:

Flutter → send JSON → Node (Dagre) → return positioned graph


Why:

zero pain
mature ecosystem
easy to tweak
⚠️ Alternative (harder)
Dart graph libs (limited)
Eclipse Layout Kernel via WASM
4. 📦 Store positioned graph (important)

Now your model becomes:

{
  "nodes": [
    { "id": "user", "x": 100, "y": 50, "width": 120, "height": 60 }
  ]
}


👉 This is your source of truth from now on

5. 🎨 Flutter Rendering

Use:

CustomPainter (do not use WebView unless you must)
You implement:
Draw nodes:
rectangles / rounded boxes
Draw edges:
straight or orthogonal lines
Add:
zoom (scale transform)
pan (translate)
6. 🖱️ Interaction Layer
Drag

On drag:

node.x += dx;
node.y += dy;

Delete
nodes.removeWhere((n) => n.id == targetId);
edges.removeWhere((e) => e.from == targetId || e.to == targetId);

Zoom / Pan

Maintain:

double scale;
Offset offset;


Apply to canvas transform.

7. 🔄 Layout strategy (HYBRID like draw.io)

This is the key design decision 👇

Mode 1: Initial auto-layout
Run Dagre once
Store positions
Mode 2: Manual editing
User drags nodes
You DO NOT re-run layout automatically
Optional:

Add button:

[ Re-layout ]


👉 Re-runs Dagre using current graph

🧠 Important design rules (don’t skip)
❗ Rule 1: Layout runs only once (by default)

If you re-run layout after every change:
→ user loses control
→ very frustrating UX

❗ Rule 2: Positions override layout

Once node has:

x, y


→ that is truth

❗ Rule 3: Keep graph + UI state separate
Graph model (nodes, edges)
UI state (selected, dragging, zoom)

🧩 Optional upgrades (worth adding later)
✅ Snap to grid
cleaner diagrams
✅ Edge routing
avoid overlapping lines
✅ Node grouping (clusters)
improves layout quality
✅ Save/load diagrams
just persist JSON
🆚 Why this works better than Mermaid

With Mermaid:

layout ✅
interaction ❌

With your pipeline:

layout ✅ (via Dagre)
interaction ✅ (via Flutter)
control ✅
🔥 Minimal implementation plan (do this in order)
Step 1
Hardcode JSON graph
Render in Flutter
Step 2
Add Dagre service
Auto-layout nodes
Step 3
Add drag support
Step 4
Add zoom/pan
Step 5
Connect LLM → JSON

👉 This avoids debugging everything at once

🧾 Final takeaway

You are basically building a mini draw.io powered by an LLM

And the winning pattern is:

LLM = structure
Layout engine = aesthetics
Flutter = control + interaction


